
[1]treacle

   TRE'ACLE, n. [L. theriaca; Gr. a wild beast.]

   1. The spume of sugar in sugar refineries. Treacle is obtained in
   refining sugar; molasses is the drainings of crude sugar. Treacle
   however is often used for molasses.

   2. A saccharine fluid, consisting of the inspissated juices or
   decoctions of certain vegetables, as the sap of the birch, sycamore,
   &c.

   3. A medicinal compound of various ingredients. [See Theriaca.]
